{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Unchecked ERC20 arithmetic lets arbitrary callers drain approved-none balances","locations":["0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:252","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:255","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:257","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:343"],"claim":"The contract uses Solidity 0.7.0 without checked arithmetic. In the ERC20 branch of `transferFrom`, `allowance[from][msg.sender]` is decremented with raw subtraction and never validated first. When allowance is zero or too small, it underflows instead of reverting, and execution continues into `_transfer`, which also performs unchecked balance arithmetic.","impact":"Any account holding fungible balance can have that balance stolen without approval as long as the attacker requests an amount that does not trigger the later burn-loop failure. Liquidity pool balances are equally exposed, enabling direct theft of tradable funds.","paths":["Call `transferFrom(victim, attacker, amount)` with `amount > minted` so the ERC20 path is taken, while `allowance[victim][attacker] == 0`.","Line 255 underflows the allowance instead of reverting.","If `victim` has at least `amount`, `_transfer` moves the tokens to the attacker and updates balances with no authorization check ever succeeding."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Transfer gate becomes a honeypot by permanently blocking sells to the chosen pool address after 50 blocks","locations":["0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:313","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:315","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:316","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:317","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/pandorasblock404.sol:18"],"claim":"`_preTransferCheck` records the first transfer recipient as `_uniswapV3Pool` and, once `_disableTransferBlock` expires 50 blocks later, reverts every transfer to that address unless the sender is whitelisted. The deployer is whitelisted at construction, so privileged addresses can still exit while ordinary holders cannot.","impact":"If the chosen address is the trading pool, non-whitelisted users can buy but are later unable to sell back into liquidity, creating a direct honeypot and permanent fund lock for public holders.","paths":["The first transfer that sets `_uniswapV3Pool` points it at the launch liquidity pool or any other chosen recipient.","After `block.number > _disableTransferBlock`, any `transfer`, `transferFrom`, or `safeTransferFrom` to that address by a non-whitelisted holder reverts with `Transfers are disabled to sell tokens`.","Whitelisted insiders retain the ability to move or sell while non-whitelisted buyers are trapped."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Buyers only get a two-block window to sell back to the pool","locations":["0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:322","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:324","0xddadf1bf44363d07e750c20219c2347ed7d826b9/contracts/ERC404.sol:325"],"claim":"Whenever tokens are received from `_uniswapV3Pool`, the recipient's `initialBuyBlock` is stored. Any later transfer back to `_uniswapV3Pool` reverts once more than two blocks have passed since that recorded buy.","impact":"Even before the broader 50-block sell freeze activates, ordinary buyers effectively have only a two-block exit window. Holding longer makes their position unsellable into the pool, which can trap user funds almost immediately after purchase.","paths":["A user buys from the designated pool, setting `initialBuyBlock[user] = block.number`.","After waiting at least three blocks, the user attempts to transfer tokens back to the pool.","`_preTransferCheck` reverts with `Transfers are disabled after 2 block of initial buy`."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"safeTransferFrom lacks authorization verification","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Incorrect. Both `safeTransferFrom` overloads delegate to `transferFrom`, and the NFT branch of `transferFrom` enforces owner/approval/operator authorization before moving the token."},{"title":"Ownership revocation permanently locks contract","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`revokeOwnership()` is an intentional renounce-ownership pattern. It may freeze admin functionality, but that is not a protocol vulnerability or user-funds issue by itself."},{"title":"Missing zero address validation in setWhitelist","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Owner-only configuration issue with no realistic standalone exploit path or protocol-level harm."},{"title":"Burn/mint loops may exceed gas limits for large transfers","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Under normal operation the native supply is only 200 tokens, so the burn/mint loops are bounded. Pathological huge-loop behavior depends on the separate unchecked-arithmetic bug already captured in F-001."},{"title":"ownerOf reverts instead of returning address(0) for non-existent IDs","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"False premise. Standard ERC721 `ownerOf` behavior is to revert for nonexistent tokens, not return `address(0)`."},{"title":"Unverified token allocation to owner at deployment","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Initial token allocation/distribution policy is a project design choice, not a smart-contract vulnerability."},{"title":"Monotonic minted counter causes permanent ERC20/ERC721 type confusion","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Code support exists, but the misclassification threshold is measured in raw 18-decimal base units. At this 200-token scale it only affects dust-sized amounts, making the impact too weak to keep as a reportable protocol issue."}]}
